------------------------------------------\nName  | Tracing | Description\n/     | false   | Default virtual host\n/app  | false   | (no description set)\n\nTracing is disabled on all vhosts (correct — tracing writes sensitive\nmessage content to a special exchange and should only be enabled\ntemporarily during debugging).\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n4. USERS AND AUTHENTICATION\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nUser      | Tags\nadmin     | [administrator]\napp-user  | [] (no management access)\n\nNote: The built-in \"guest\" user does NOT appear in the user list, meaning\nit has been explicitly removed. Good practice.\n\n[FINDING C-2 — MEDIUM] The configuration file contains:\n    loopback_users.guest = false\nThis disables the loopback restriction on the guest user. Although the\nguest user does not currently exist, this setting means that if a \"guest\"\naccount is ever created it will be reachable from any network address\nrather than localhost only. The risk is latent; it should be removed or\nset to `true` to enforce the safe default.\n\n[FINDING C-3 — MEDIUM] Only two authentication mechanisms are enabled:\nPLAIN and AMQPLAIN. Both transmit credentials in cleartext over the AMQP\nwire. Without TLS on the AMQP listener (see C-6), credentials are exposed\nto any observer on the pod network. Consider adding EXTERNAL (certificate-\nbased) auth once TLS is configured.\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n5. PERMISSIONS\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nVirtual host \"/\"  (default):\n  admin      | configure=.* | write=.* | read=.*\n\nVirtual host \"/app\":\n  admin      | configure=.* | write=.* | read=.*\n  app-user   | configure=.* | write=.* | read=.*\n\n[FINDING C-4 — HIGH] app-user has full configure/write/read permissions\n(regex \".*\") on the /app vhost. A well-scoped application user should only\nhave write permission on queues it publishes to, and read permission on\nqueues it consumes from. Configure permission should be empty (\"\") unless\nthe application creates its own topology at startup. Over-provisioned\npermissions mean a compromised application credential can alter or delete\nany resource in /app.\n\n[FINDING C-5 — MEDIUM] The admin user retains full wildcard access to both\nvhosts. Consider creating a separate, scoped user for automated management\ntasks rather than using the single shared admin credential everywhere.\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n6. TLS / TRANSPORT SECURITY\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nListeners found:\n  Port 5672  — AMQP 0-9-1 / AMQP 1.0  (plaintext TCP)\n  Port 15672 — HTTP Management API     (plaintext HTTP)\n  Port 25672 — Inter-node clustering   (plaintext TCP)\n\nNo TLS listener (port 5671 / 15671) is configured.\n\n[FINDING C-6 — CRITICAL] AMQP traffic on port 5672 is unencrypted.\nCredentials (user/password transmitted via PLAIN or AMQPLAIN) and all\nmessage payloads are visible to any party with access to the pod network\nor any network path between producers/consumers and the broker.\n\n[FINDING C-7 — HIGH] The management HTTP API on port 15672 uses plain\nHTTP, not HTTPS. Management credentials and all API responses (including\nqueue content previews, shovel credentials, etc.) traverse the network\nunencrypted.\n\n[FINDING C-8 — MEDIUM] No TLS is configured for inter-node clustering\ntraffic (port 25672 / Erlang distribution). In a multi-node deployment\ninside a shared cluster this means inter-node message forwarding and\nMnesia replication traffic is unencrypted.\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n7. POLICIES\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nNo policies are defined on any vhost.\n\n[FINDING C-9 — MEDIUM] Without policies, queues have no HA or quorum\nmirroring configuration enforced centrally. Any client can declare a queue\nwithout replicas. The current classic queue \"app-queue\" has no replica and\nwill lose unacknowledged messages if the node hosting it fails.\n\n[FINDING C-10 — LOW] There are no dead-letter policies. Messages that are\nrejected or expire silently disappear. For compliance-sensitive workloads a\ndead-letter exchange should be configured to capture and retain\nunprocessable messages.\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n8. QUEUES\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nVirtual host \"/app\":\n  Name      : app-queue\n  Type      : classic  (NOT quorum)\n  Durable   : true\n  Auto-del  : false\n  Arguments : (none — no x-message-ttl, x-max-length, x-dead-letter-exchange)\n  Messages  : 0\n  Consumers : 0\n  State     : running\n  Policy    : (none applied)\n\nVirtual host \"/\":\n  (no queues)\n\n[FINDING C-11 — MEDIUM] app-queue is a classic queue, not a quorum queue.\nClassic queues provide weaker durability guarantees; a single-node failure\ncan result in message loss even when the queue is declared durable.\nMigrating to quorum queues (supported by the enabled feature flag\n`quorum_queue`) is recommended for production workloads.\n\n[FINDING C-12 — LOW] No message TTL (x-message-ttl) or max-length\n(x-max-length / x-max-length-bytes) argument is set on app-queue. Without\nbounds, the queue can grow unbounded if consumers fall behind, potentially\nexhausting broker memory or disk.\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n9. EXCHANGES (virtual host /app)\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nAll exchanges present are standard built-in AMQP exchanges:\n  (default)           direct   durable\n  amq.direct          direct   durable\n  amq.fanout          fanout   durable\n  amq.headers         headers  durable\n  amq.match           headers  durable\n  amq.topic           topic    durable\n  amq.rabbitmq.trace  topic    durable\n\nNo custom exchanges are defined. The trace exchange (amq.rabbitmq.trace)\nis present but vhost tracing is disabled (no active bindings).\n\nBindings on /app:\n  (default exchange) -> app-queue  routing-key=app-queue  (standard auto-binding)\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n10. RESOURCE LIMITS\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nPer-user limits  : none (admin, app-user — both unlimited)\nPer-vhost limits : none (/, /app — both unlimited)\n\n[FINDING C-13 — LOW] No per-user connection or channel limits are\nconfigured. A misbehaving or compromised client can exhaust broker\nconnection slots. Set x-max-connections and x-max-channels per user as a\ndefence-in-depth measure.\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n11. CONFIGURATION FILE REVIEW (/etc/rabbitmq/rabbitmq.conf)\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\ncluster_formation.peer_discovery_backend = rabbit_peer_discovery_k8s\ncluster_formation.k8s.host = kubernetes.default.svc.cluster.local\ncluster_formation.k8s.service_name = rabbitmq-headless\ncluster_formation.k8s.address_type = hostname\ncluster_formation.k8s.hostname_suffix = .<ns>.svc.cluster.local\ncluster_partition_handling = pause_minority        <- CORRECT\nqueue_master_locator = min-masters                <- load-balanced\nloopback_users.guest = false                      <- see C-2\nlisteners.tcp.default = 5672                      <- plaintext only, see C-6\nmanagement.tcp.port = 15672                       <- plaintext only, see C-7\n\ncluster_partition_handling = pause_minority is a good choice: the minority\npartition suspends itself rather than continuing to accept writes,\npreventing split-brain data divergence.\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n12. PLUGINS ENABLED\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nrabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s     — Kubernetes peer discovery\nrabbitmq_peer_discovery_common  — (dependency)\nrabbitmq_management             — HTTP management API and UI\nrabbitmq_management_agent       — (dependency)\nrabbitmq_web_dispatch           — (dependency)\namqp_client / cowboy / cowlib   — (dependencies)\n\n[FINDING C-14 — INFO] The management plugin exposes a full admin UI and\nREST API on port 15672. No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy was observed in the\nnamespace. Restrict network access to port 15672 with a NetworkPolicy so\nit is not reachable from arbitrary pods in the cluster.\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n13. KUBERNETES RESOURCE REVIEW\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nStatefulSet resources field: {} (no CPU/memory requests or limits set)\nSecrets:\n  rabbitmq-admin         Opaque  (admin user credentials)\n  rabbitmq-app           Opaque  (app-user credentials)\n  rabbitmq-erlang-cookie Opaque  (Erlang clustering cookie)\n\n[FINDING C-15 — MEDIUM] No CPU/memory requests or limits are configured on\nthe rabbitmq StatefulSet containers. The broker can consume unbounded node\nresources, causing noisy-neighbour interference and preventing capacity\nplanning. Set appropriate requests and limits.\n\n[FINDING C-16 — INFO] No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy exists in this namespace.\nAll pods can reach AMQP port 5672 and management port 15672 from any\nnamespace. A NetworkPolicy should restrict AMQP access to only authorised\nconsumer/producer workloads and restrict management API access to operator\nor CI tooling namespaces.\n\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\n14. FINDINGS SUMMARY TABLE\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nID    | Severity | Area             | Title\n------|----------|------------------|------------------------------------------\nC-1   | HIGH     | Version          | RabbitMQ 3.12.14 is out of support\nC-2   | MEDIUM   | Auth config      | loopback_users.guest=false latent risk\nC-3   | MEDIUM   | Auth mechanisms  | Only PLAIN/AMQPLAIN; no cert-based auth\nC-4   | HIGH     | Permissions      | app-user has wildcard configure+write+read\nC-5   | MEDIUM   | Permissions      | Single shared admin credential\nC-6   | CRITICAL | TLS              | No TLS on AMQP port 5672\nC-7   | HIGH     | TLS              | Management API on plaintext HTTP (15672)\nC-8   | MEDIUM   | TLS              | No TLS on inter-node clustering traffic\nC-9   | MEDIUM   | Policies         | No HA/quorum policies enforced\nC-10  | LOW      | Policies         | No dead-letter policy\nC-11  | MEDIUM   | Queue type       | app-queue is classic, not quorum\nC-12  | LOW      | Queue limits     | No message TTL or max-length on app-queue\nC-13  | LOW      | Resource limits  | No per-user connection/channel limits\nC-14  | INFO     | Network          | No NetworkPolicy limiting port 15672\nC-15  | MEDIUM   | K8s resources    | No CPU/memory requests or limits set\nC-16  | INFO     | Network          | No NetworkPolicy in namespace\n\nCritical: 1  |  High: 3  |  Medium: 7  |  Low: 3  |  Info: 2\n\nNo changes were made to the cluster during this audit.\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nEND OF AUDIT REPORT\n---------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINDINGS_EOF\necho \"Written: $(wc -l < /tmp/findings.txt) lines\"","description":"Write findings report to /tmp/findings.txt"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4611,"cache_read_input_tokens":44384,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4611},"output_tokens":43,"ser